vectorData.altText: 6. A small subset of the muscles of the anterior compartment of the forearm are innervated by the _____ nerve.
That's right!  The ulnar nerve innervates flexor carpi ulnaris and the medial half of flexor digitorum profundus (digits 4 & 5).
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The two muscles that pronate the forearm are also in this compartment. Both have the word pronator in their names. 
Because these are the primary actions of the muscles of the anterior compartment of the forearm, it is described, functionally, as the “flexor-pronator compartment”.
All muscles in this compartment are innervated by the median nerve, with one-and-a-half exceptions. The exceptions are innervated by the ulnar nerve. 
The muscles are organized into three layers. 
The superficial layer consists of four muscles (red). One is a pronator of the forearm, and the other three muscles flex the wrist joint.

The middle layer consists of one muscle (green) that flexes the MCP and PIP joints of the four fingers.
The deep layer consists of two muscles (blue). One is the only muscle that flexes the DIP joints of the four fingers. The other is the only muscle that flexes the interphalangeal joint of the thumb.
Notice: the deeper the muscle, the more distal its insertion, and therefore, the more distal its action.

Tendons arising from the muscles of the anterior compartment of the forearm cross the anterior aspect of the wrist and digits; they therefore act to flex the wrist, MCP, PIP and DIP joints     . Many of these muscles have the word flexor in their names.

MCP metacarpophalangeal joints
PIP proximal interphalangeal joints
DIP distal interphalangeal joints
